Modeling White Wine Quality¶

Project Overview¶

In this project, I will be using classification techniques to predict the quality of white wine based on the physicochemical testing results. The model will predict if a wine is good or bad (binary classsification). I will test these 3 modeling methods: Logistic Regression, Gaussian Naive Bayes, and Gradient Boosting. Since I like white wine, my goal is to learn more about what is important in determining white wine quality and, hopefully, find new wines to try.

Data Overview¶

The data for the project will come from here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality.

Citation:

P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

Available at: [@Elsevier] http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016 </br> [Pre-press (pdf)] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/winequality09.pdf </br> [bib] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/dss09.bib </br>

The original source contains data for both red and white wine from the north of Portugal. This project will only be using the white wine dataset. The feature variables are objective physicochemical tests and the target variable, quality, is based on sensory data using the median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts. Each expert graded the wine quality between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

The dataset is a single table (266KB in size) consisting of 4898 observations and 12 attributes. All attributes are numeric. A summary of the variables are provided below.

Feature Variables:

  • fixed acidity (continuous float values)
  • volatile acidity (continuous float values)
  • citric acid (continuous float values)
  • residual sugar (continuous float values)
  • chlorides (continuous float values)
  • free sulfur dioxide (continuous float values)
  • total sulfur dioxide (continuous float values)
  • density (continuous float values)
  • pH (continuous float values)
  • sulphates (continuous float values)
  • alcohol (continuous float values)

Target Variable:

  • quality (categorical integer score between 0 and 10)

After looking through the dataset, there doesn't appear to be any missing values or entries that would be considered an outlier. All features will be kept and none need to have any imputation done.

I will now look at the originally provided quality column. Since quality is provided as multiple cartegories, I will transform this into only 2 categories representing good and bad wines.

Since I am only interested in whether or not a wine is good or bad, the quality column will be updated to reflect this logic:

  • A wine is considered good if the quality is >= 6. This will be encoded as a 1.
  • A wine is considered bad if the quality is <6. This will be encoded as a 0.
1    3258

Additionally, I noticed that there a small issue with class imbalance in the dataset. The number of good wines is almost double the amount of bad wines. For now, nothing will be done differently due to this since the imbalance isn't extreme.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

When looking at this pairplot of all of the data, there appears to be no obvious colinearity amongst the features. The only features that appear to be correlated are density and residual sugar.

When looking at the heatmap, its easier to see that there is a strong positive correlation between density and residual sugar. There is also a strong negative correlation between density and alcohol. There doesn't appear to be any good single predictors for the target variable, quality. The best single predictor based on correlation is alcohol, but its only has a correlation of 0.4.

It is difficult to determine which features will be needed for modeling, so for now, all features will be kept. Its possible some features will get dropped later that have almost no correlation like citric acid and free sulfur dioxide.

I will now check to see if any of the features are normally distributed using the Shapiro-Wilk Test. The null hypothesis for this test is that the data comes from a normal distribution. So if the p-value is < 0.05, we will reject this null hypothesis and say that the data isn't likely coming from a normal distribution.

p-value for fixed_acidity is 1.16e-27
p-value for volatile_acidity is 0.00e+00
p-value for citric_acid is 9.81e-45
p-value for residual_sugar is 0.00e+00
p-value for chlorides is 0.00e+00
p-value for free_sulfur_dioxide is 3.85e-40
p-value for total_sulfur_dioxide is 4.40e-19
p-value for density is 1.78e-36
p-value for pH is 6.51e-20
p-value for sulphates is 1.82e-37
p-value for alcohol is 2.56e-36

For all features, the p-value is below 0.05. This means we do not have evidence to say that the features are derived from normal distributions.

Model Experimentation and Intermediate Results¶

I will test out 3 classification models in this section, Logistic Regression, Gaussian Naive Bayes, and Gradient Boosting. To set up this section, I am creating the training and testing sets. The training set will use 30% of the data. A scaled version of the feature columns are also created so that they can be used for models that benefit from scaled features.

This function, forward_selection, will be used for models that are going to use forward selection to determine the best features to use to maximize accuracy. During each feature selection test, 5-fold cross-validation is used to calculate the average accuracy when adding in that feature. This technique also reduces the risk of overfitting.

Logistic Regression¶

I will test out a Logistic Regression model using the forward selection method to determine the best features to use that will maximize accuracy.

Based on the results, I will use top 4 features from the experiment, in the model. After 4 features, the accuracy does not change much.

The Logistic Regression model performed fairly well with a training and testing accuracy that are almost the same at 72%.

Gradient Boosting¶

Gradient Boosting is the final model that will be tested. Grid Search will be used to do hyper-parameter tuning with 5-fold cross-validation.

Grid Search Parameters:

{'max_depth': array([ 3,  5,  7,  9, 12]),
 'n_estimators': array([  50,  200,  350,  500,  650,  800,  950, 1100, 1250, 1400, 1550,
        1700, 1850, 2000])}
Fitting 5 folds for each of 70 candidates, totalling 350 fits

Best parameters found with grid search: {'max_depth': 7, 'n_estimators': 500}
Cross-validation score using the best parameters: 0.8261

Gradient Boosting Training Accuracy (using best parameters): 1.0000
Gradient Boosting Testing Accuracy (using best parameters): 0.8190

To summarize the Gradient Boosting grid search results, the best accuracy was found when using a max_depth of 7 and n_estimators equal to 500. When looking at all cross-validation results in the chart above, it doesn't appear that many of the models got much better after a certain number of estimators. All of the models are able to be between 81% and 83% accuracy at some combination on max_depth and n_estimators. To make a simplified model and to avoid overfitting, I will chose a different model from what was given by the grid search results. Using a max_depth of 5 appears to be a good choice since its close to the same accuracy as the other max_depth values. I'll also choose n_estimators equal to 200 since it appears that the accuracy doesn't get much better after that as well.

Final Model with Results¶

After testing the Logistic Regression, Gaussian Naive Bayes, and the Gradient Boosting models, I decided to go with the Gradient Boosting model since it provided the best overall results. For this model, I will use a max_depth of 5 and an n_estimators of 200.

Gradient Boosting Training Accuracy: 0.9743
Gradient Boosting Testing Accuracy: 0.8156

Ultimately, reducing the max_depth and the n_estimators, results in roughly the same model as chosing the best estimator from the grid search earlier. This model is the best model overall for the test set, when comparing to Logistic Regression and Gaussian Naive Bayes.

Based on the feature importance results, it looks like alcohol and volatile_acidity are the top 2 features, just like they were in the Logistic Regression and Gaussian Naive Bayes models. I will keep all of the features in the model, since the Gradient Boosting model still performs well when faced with many features.

The plot above shows what the data separation looks like when using the entire white wine dataset. The top 2 features, alcohol and volatile acidity, were used in order to reduce the dimensions of the dataset and make it easier to visualize. There does appear to be clusters for good wine and bad wine, but there is quite a bit of overlap.

Now, let take a look at the precision and recall for the training and testing set.

Training Precision: 0.9696
Training Recall: 0.9931

Testing Precision: 0.8330
Testing Recall: 0.8936

The testing results for precision and recall are quite good, and turned out to be even higher than accuracy. Accuracy was the main testing criteria, but having good precision and recall suggests the model works well under imbalanced conditions. Having good accuracy was chosen as the main testing criteria since generally classifying good wine was important to my overall goal of finding good wines.

The ROC results suggests that the thresholds currently in the model works well. So if there is a probability >0.5, then the entry would go to the positive class (good wine).

Conclusions¶

Something I enjoyed with this project, was taking an analysis from start to finish. I liked coming up with the overall process for doing the EDA and modeling. As far as the practicality of implementing this model, I am not sure a regular person would be able to gather the required features for the wine. If the company provided this data, then it could be used. It is still interesting to know what typically contributes to a good white wine.

The gradient boosting model worked really well, but I would have liked to have tuned other hyperparameters to see what other model was possible. I did experiment with a few other hyperparameters, but the training time was quite long, so I stuck with only 2. It didn't work for me to have more than 2 parameters since the training time would double. Having a max depth of 3 didn't have good performance since there weren't enough trees or the learning rate was too low. I think I could have made a better model if I had a more powerful machine so that I could test out many more hyperparameters. I could also likely improve by taking the 2 hyperparameters I have currently, and doing another grid search for additional ones. This would risk overfitting, so I didn't take that approach.
